# **FASTA/FASTQ file format** {#fasta/fastq-file-format}

FASTA and FASTQ are (to my knowledge) the two most common file formats for sequencing reads and are likely what we will get from the sequencing lab. The details on the format of these files are not super important, but it does inform some of the parameters set for pre-filtering the data later on so it’s worth a quick overview.

[FASTA](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FASTA_format) is essentially a text file with multiple sequences, each sequence represented by a letter (example, a read of adenine-thymine-adenine would be ATA). There’s usually multiple reads in a FASTA file, distinguished by unique sequence identifiers.

[FASTQ](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FASTQ_format) is basically just a FASTA file where each sequenced nucleotide is paired with a quality score. Because FASTQ (just like FASTA files) are text files, this quality score is displayed as an [ASCII](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ASCII) character. Quality scores are stored as values ranging from 33 (in binary, this is 0010 0001, in hexadecimal this is 0x21) to 126 (0111 1110 or 0x7e) (on the FASTQ wikipedia page they are listed as hexadecimal values, so I wanted to include both here). These values are displayed as ASCII characters from “\!” (the character corresponding to 33 decimal or 0x21 hex) to “\~” (126 or 0x7e). 

![][image1]

This is a great example of a FASTQ snippet from the Wiki page:

@SEQ\_ID  
GATTTGGGGTTCAAAGCAGTATCGATCAAATAGTAAATCCATTTGTTCAACTCACAGTTT  
\+  
\!''\*((((\*\*\*+))%%%++)(%%%%).1\*\*\*-+\*''))\*\*55CCF\>\>\>\>\>\>CCCCCCC65

In our first step of the analysis, we will need to pre-filter any low quality reads. The program we will use for this does not know that the quality scores are from 33 to 126, so one of the parameters we will pass to the program is to start counting at 33 instead of counting from 1\.

# **Pre-Processing** {#pre-processing}

There are a couple of steps we are going to take before we start analyzing the sequences. First, any low-quality reads will be removed. Then, if our samples were paired-end sequenced (sequenced forwards and backwards) then we will merge the forward and backward reads together (I believe this assumes that the forward and reverse sequences are long enough to overlap, I don’t know if that’s the case for our samples- this is probably something to double check). Then there’s a couple more filtering steps after this as well.

## **FastX-Toolkit** {#fastx-toolkit}

**\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\***

**\*\*Quick Install\*\***

**The following information is useful for understanding how to install FastX-Toolkit. If you just want to install FastX without entering all the code yourself, just type this into your terminal, one line at a time:**

**$ wget https://raw.githubusercontent.com/JeffreyDeanBrown/HembryLabSequencing/main/install\_fastx-toolkit.sh**  
**$ sudo bash install\_fastx-toolkit.sh**

**This just runs all of the following code for you, so you don’t have to do it yourself. Read on to learn about the code in this script-**

**\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\***

The [FastX-Toolkit](http://hannonlab.cshl.edu/fastx_toolkit/) ([libutils github](https://github.com/agordon/libgtextutils) and the [toolkit github](https://github.com/agordon/fastx_toolkit)) was used by the reference paper to remove low-quality reads. Specifically, they *trimmed* the sequences (removed the low quality base-calls, but leaving the rest of the sequence alone) and removed any sequences that were shorter than 120 bases following trimming. 

The reference paper used the following parameters for the fastq\_quality\_trimmer command:

**\-Q 33** (this lets the trimmer know that quality scores start at 33, or ascii character “\!”, for FASTQ file format)  
**\-t 20**  (quality threshold, anything scored below 20 is trimmed)  
**\-l 120** (minimum length, anything smaller than 120 after trimming is discarded)

The FastX-Toolkit was last updated in 2014, and is currently outdated. There are some more modern programs out there that we can also use, but we can also patch the code pretty easily and still install it. The patch and installation instructions are as follows:

### **Fixing & installing the libutils:** {#fixing-&-installing-the-libutils:}

- **Patches/Fixes:** Per [this stackoverflow post](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/38659115/make-fails-with-error-cannot-convert-stdistream-aka-stdbasic-istreamchar), there was an update to C++ (C++11, specifically) where certain code has to be specifically labeled as a certain class, where it didn’t matter before (there are some interesting links on the stackoverflow post if you are interested in learning more).  
  - To download, patch, and install the libutils, simply run the following:  
      
    *(copy and paste everything after the dollar sign into your command line. If a line wraps to a second line, copy and paste the whole thing. Anything after “\#” is a comment and not code, and doesn’t need to be copied or pasted)*

## `# download the libutils file`

## `$ curl -LO https://github.com/agordon/libgtextutils/releases/download/0.7/libgtextutils-0.7.tar.gz`

`# unpack the compressed file containing the utils (.tar is referred to as a`   
`# “tarball”, similar to a .zip or a .rar file if those are more familiar)`  
`$ tar -xzf libgtextutils-0.7.tar.gz`

`# switch to the libutils directory`  
`$ cd libgtextutils-0.7/`

`# make the changes to the code (see the description below for an explanation of this command)`

## `$ sed -i '47s/input_stream/static_cast<bool>(input_stream)/' src/gtextutils/text_line_reader.cpp`

## 

## `# install the updated code`

`$ ./configure`  
`$ make`  
`$ sudo make install`

`# delete all the files now that you have installed the software:`  
`$ cd ..`  
`$ rm -r libgtextutils-0.7/`  
`$ rm libgtextutils-0.7.tar.gz`

This uses some interesting commands, the first one is sed (“[stream editor](https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/sed-command-in-linux-unix-with-examples/)”) which, in this case, goes to line 47 of the file src/gtextutils/text\_line\_reader.cpp and substitutes the text “input\_stream” with “static\_cast\<bool\>(input\_stream)”. This is the edit that is needed for the changes made in C++11.

### **Fixing & Installing the toolkit:** {#fixing-&-installing-the-toolkit:}

- **Patches/Fixes:**  
  - Another update from C++17 ([this one in particular](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/language/attributes/fallthrough), if you’re curious) creates a compiling error (per [this issue](https://github.com/agordon/fastx_toolkit/issues/14) posted on the fastx-toolkit github). This can be quickly fixed by downloading the patch posted on the github issue.   
    - There is also an issue with compiling using clang (the compiler for macOS), from [this github issue report](https://github.com/agordon/fastx_toolkit/issues/20) and another compiling error from an unused variable from [this report](https://github.com/agordon/fastx_toolkit/issues/28). All three of these bugs are fixed in the following code  
  - Download, patch, and install the toolkit with the following commands:  
    

## `$ curl -LO https://github.com/agordon/fastx_toolkit/releases/download/0.0.14/fastx_toolkit-0.0.14.tar.bz2`

## `$ tar -xjf fastx_toolkit-0.0.14.tar.bz2`

## 

## `$ cd fastx_toolkit-0.0.14/`

## `$ curl -LO https://raw.githubusercontent.com/JeffreyDeanBrown/HembryLabSequencing/main/MacOSPatch.txt`

## `$ patch < MacOSPatch.txt`

## `$ curl -LO https://github.com/agordon/fastx_toolkit/files/1182724/fastx-toolkit-gcc7-patch.txt`

## `$ patch  -p1 < fastx-toolkit-gcc7-patch.txt`

## `$ sed -i '88,90d;58d' src/fastx_artifacts_filter/fastx_artifacts_filter.c` 

## `$ ./configure`

## `$ make`

## `$ sudo make install`

## `$ cd ..`

## `$ rm -r fastx_toolkit-0.0.14/`

## `$ rm fastx_toolkit-0.0.14.tar.bz2`

And you’re done\! This uses some cool command line techniques, including the “\<” symbol, which redirects the text in the patch.txt file into something called the [standard input](https://www.digitalocean.com/community/tutorials/an-introduction-to-linux-i-o-redirection).

### **Running the fastx toolkit:** {#running-the-fastx-toolkit:}

- To use the toolkit, simply open up a terminal in the directory where your .fastq file is located and run the code:


## 

## `# replace “input_file.fastq” with the name of your sequencing data file, and` 

## `# replace “trimmed_file.fastq” with whatever you want to name your newly`

## `# trimmed file`

## 

## `$ fastq_quality_trimmer -Q 33 -t 20 -l 130 -i input_file.fastq -o trimmed_file.fastq -v`

Your newly trimmed file will be saved as whatever name you enter after \-o (for “output”). If you want to change the trim value or length value from what the reference paper used, then now’s the time to do it. However, do not change the value of the \-Q parameter, as \-Q 33 is required for any fastq file format.

## **fastQC** {#fastqc}

Fastqc ([link](https://www.bioinformatics.babraham.ac.uk/projects/fastqc/)) is a great little java program that shows you some basic stats and information about a fastq file. It’s straightforward to install and download, feel free to send me an email if you have questions.

fastQC is totally optional, but it might be handy/fun to try out. If you want to adjust the trim values and length values used by fastq\_quality\_trimmer in the last step, I would recommend using fastQC to get an idea of what the overall quality scores are for your sequenced data to help you adjust the values of the trim.

## **PEAR** {#pear}

Pear (doi: [10.1093/bioinformatics/btt593](https://doi.org/10.1093%2Fbioinformatics%2Fbtt593)) is a paired-end read merger, it merges the forward and backward reads from a paired-end read as long as they overlap ([here’s](https://www.drive5.com/usearch/manual/merge_pair.html) a short webpage about merging). The new link for the software is [here](https://www.h-its.org/software/pear-paired-end-read-merger/) (the paper’s published link is no longer correct). The way PEAR is set up, you need to “purchase it” (it’s free) to have it emailed to you (I believe they do this to ensure it’s only used for academic purposes). “Purchase” it here [https://www.h-its.org/downloads/pear-academic/](https://www.h-its.org/downloads/pear-academic/).

**\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\***

**\*\*Quick Install\*\***

**Once you have downloaded pear, you can run the following script to automatically install pear. Just make sure you are in the directory containing the pear code (type “ln” in the console to list all of the files in your directory, and make sure one of them looks like this, but with the numbers instead of asterisks: pear-src-\*\*.\*\*.tar.gz) and type this into a terminal one line at a time:**

**$ wget https://raw.githubusercontent.com/JeffreyDeanBrown/HembryLabSequencing/main/install\_pear.sh**  
**$ sudo bash install\_pear.sh pear-src-\*\*.\*\*.tar.gz**

**But you must replace “pear-src-\*\*.\*\*.tar.gz with the name of the pear code you downloaded from pear’s website\!\! (just type pear and press tab to auto-fill the entire name at once)**

## **Prin-seq-lite** {#prin-seq-lite}

Prin-seq-lite ([https://prinseq.sourceforge.net/](https://prinseq.sourceforge.net/)) was used to remove “ambiguous” base calls, which from what I can gather are longer spans of the same base called over and over, which has been linked with erroneous base calls. They talk about it some in the manual [here](https://prinseq.sourceforge.net/manual.html#QCAMBIGUOUS), where they cite a paper that showed higher error rates with longer sections of single-base repeats

(Huse S, Huber J, Morrison H, Sogin M, Welch D: **Accuracy and quality of massively parallel DNA pyrosequencing**. *Genome Biology* 2007, **8**:R143) 

Prin-seq is super easy to use, it’s just a perl script that you download from their sourceforge. Download the script here ([https://sourceforge.net/projects/prinseq/files/standalone/](https://sourceforge.net/projects/prinseq/files/standalone/)), I downloaded prinseq-lite-0.20.4.tar.gz (latest version at the time of writing this) but other versions are available on the same page.

Decompress the tarball

## `$ tar -xzf prinseq-lite-0.20.4.tar.gz`

Copy prinseq-lite.pl (.pl is a perl script) to the directory that has your fastq files, and run it using this command (this is just one command, paste everything after the $ at the same time)

## `$ perl prinseq-lite.pl -verbose -fastq file.fastq -ns_max_n 0 -out_good file_no_ns.fastq -out_bad file_with_ns.fastq`

Replace **file.fastq** with the name of your fastq file, change **file\_no\_ns.fastq** to name the file that will **not** have ambiguous bases, and change **file\_with\_ns.fastq** to name the file that will have **only** the ambiguous bases.

# **Automated Processing Scripts** {#automated-processing-scripts}

To make it so you don’t have to manually merge or trim every sample one at a time, I've written a couple of scripts to automate things.

### **Automated Merging** {#automated-merging}

To auto-merge, put all of your samples in one directory and run the following code:

## `$ curl -LO https://raw.githubusercontent.com/JeffreyDeanBrown/HembryLabSequencing/main/peaing.sh`

## `$ bash pearing.sh your_directory_containing_sequences/`

This works by sorting reads into two directories, one titled sequences\_R1/ and one titled sequencing\_R2/ (R1 are the forward reads, R2 are the reverse reads). Then, each sample from R1/ is merged with it’s match in R2/, the merged sequence is saved in a directory titled Merged\_PEAR/, and this is repeated for every sample in R1. The script also saves a text file with all information about this merger saved for future reference, which is saved in Merged\_PEAR/merge\_\[today’s date\].txt (example: merge\_27-May-2024.txt).

The code can be reviewed on my github, the script is “pearing.sh”

This is a visual of the new directories that the script will create, a￼nd the contents of those directories:

![][image2]

### **Automated Trimming** {#automated-trimming}

To auto-trim, run the following code:

## `$ curl -LO https://raw.githubusercontent.com/JeffreyDeanBrown/HembryLabSequencing/main/trim_bulk.sh`

## `$ bash trim_bulk.sh sequences_to_be_trimmed/`

Just replace sequences\_to\_be\_trimmed/ with the name of your directory that contains your fastq files. This script works by trimming every sequence in the sequences\_to\_be\_trimmed/ directory, one at a time, and saving them in a new directory prepended with trimd\_ (so if your data is saved in \~/data/my\_data, then the trimmed data is stored in \~/data/trimd\_my\_data). The script also saves all the outputs and general statistics in a text file trimd\_\*/Trim\_Statistics.txt. 

The code can be reviewed on my github, the script is “trim\_bulk.sh”.

### **Automated Prin-seq-lite**  {#automated-prin-seq-lite}

To automatically remove ambiguous base-calls from a directory full of sequences using prinseq-lite, run the following code:

## `$ curl -LO https://raw.githubusercontent.com/JeffreyDeanBrown/HembryLabSequencing/main/rm_ambg_prinseq.sh`

## `$ bash rm_ambg_prinseq.sh sequences/to/be/cleaned/`

Just replace sequences/to/be/cleaned/ with the directory containing your fastq files that need to be processed. The script will create two new directories, clear\_\*/ and ambig\_\*/, with the processed sequences saved in clear\_\*/ and the failed (too many ambiguous basecalls) saved in ambig\_\*/. It will also output a log file to clear\_\*/prinseq\_log.txt.

The code can be reviewed on my github, the script is “rm\_ambg\_prinseq.sh”
